{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487436"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"346"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/346"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.52,0.25,0.16,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112550"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/346"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"347"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15059"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112550"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents with a three week history of a painless swelling which has gradually increased in size within the right anterior triangle of her neck. She does not report any associated symptoms such as pain, difficulty swallowing or voice hoarseness. She denies any recent infection or trauma to the area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the skin overlying the swelling appears normal (Image). The swelling is soft and fluctuant to palpate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following embryological origins is most commonly associated with this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["First branchial cleft","Second branchial cleft","Third branchial cleft","Fourth branchial cleft","Fifth branchial cleft"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is the classical presentation for a branchial cyst. This congenital cyst represents a failure of obliteration of the \u003Cstrong\u003Esecond branchial cleft \u003C/strong\u003Ein embryonic development. The second branchial arch is the most common embryological structure responsible for 95% of all branchial arch cyst. The cyst characteristically appears in the second or third decade of life as a painless swelling situated on the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, one-third of the way down that structure. Although benign, surgery may be indicated as the cyst can compress nearby structure including the jugular vein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efirst branchial cleft \u003C/strong\u003Eaccounts for 5-25% of all branchial cysts. There are two types of cysts from the first branchial cleft - the first presents as a preauricular cyst, and the second is along the angle of the mandible, submandibular and periauricular area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethird branchial cleft \u003C/strong\u003Ecysts typically occurs on the left side, in the lower portion of the anterior neck which may be confused for an abscess, malignancy or thyroiditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efourth branchial cleft \u003C/strong\u003Ecyst is rare, and typically presents in the anterior neck, looping around cranial nerve XII, running posterior to the common carotid artery and thyroid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBranchial arch cysts only affects arches one to four. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efifth branchial cleft \u003C/strong\u003Etypically degenerates and does not contribute to the formation of the branchial arch cysts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The second branchial arch is most associated with the formation of branchial cysts"],"references":["Coste AH, Lofgren DH, Shermetaro C. Branchial cleft cyst. StatPearls Publishing. 2018 May. Available at: https://europepmc.org/article/NBK/nbk499914","Allen SB, Jamal Z, Goldman J. Branchial Cleft Cysts. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482467/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94584"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"346"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"13966"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"13966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/13966"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e58304b0-d15c-4453-844b-ec0e01a68c52.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e58304b0-d15c-4453-844b-ec0e01a68c52.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94584"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T14:44:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T14:44:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"346"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112550"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHea